01:40.760 --> 01:42.637
Then my mind drifted to the dinner party.

01:44.280 --> 01:45.759
And the Architectural Digest.

01:46.960 --> 01:48.176
She has a teenage daughter.

01:48.200 --> 01:49.315
They call that...

01:49.400 --> 01:51.436
- Oh, is that it? Okay.
- Yeah.

01:51.520 --> 01:53.456
We were talking about cheese.
You got to try this.

01:53.480 --> 01:55.471
This is, like, an imitation ComtÃ©.

01:55.560 --> 01:57.080
- Really?
- But instead of organic...

01:58.520 --> 02:00.476
Isn't that
your friend from college?

02:01.440 --> 02:03.192
Brad has this friend from college...

02:03.280 --> 02:05.589
I knew Nick had become
rich and successful, but...

02:06.960 --> 02:08.359
I felt gut-punched.

02:10.639 --> 02:12.835
I felt like the world was
rubbing my nose in something.

02:25.120 --> 02:27.475
So many friends from college
have become successful.

02:34.480 --> 02:36.835
Nick Pascale was
a big movie director in Hollywood,

02:37.600 --> 02:39.795
living this crazy, decadent life.

02:44.160 --> 02:45.878
Jason Hatfield had his own hedge fund.

02:47.160 --> 02:48.388
Obscenely rich.

02:49.560 --> 02:50.709
Owns three houses.

02:51.720 --> 02:52.835
Big philanthropist.

02:55.840 --> 02:57.831
Billy Wearslter sold
his tech company at 40.

02:58.840 --> 03:02.071
He's already retired,
living a life of leisure in Maui.

03:06.840 --> 03:08.440
Craig Fisher worked for the White House.

03:09.360 --> 03:10.800
He's written all these best-sellers.

03:11.560 --> 03:12.595
Always on TV.

03:30.360 --> 03:31.998
It's stupid to compare lives.

03:32.960 --> 03:33.960
But when I do,

03:35.440 --> 03:36.714
I feel somehow I failed.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.070
And over time, these feelings get worse.

03:51.720 --> 03:52.789
Brad.
Shit.

03:52.920 --> 03:53.920
Oh, my.
Sorry.

03:54.320 --> 03:55.320
You okay?

03:56.240 --> 03:58.959
What the hell?
You just... you just hit me in the face.

03:59.560 --> 04:00.560
Oh, sorry.

04:00.680 --> 04:01.954
It's okay.

04:03.320 --> 04:04.639
Can't sleep.
Mm.

04:07.360 --> 04:09.360
How much do you think
your parents' house is worth?

04:10.760 --> 04:12.079
My parents' house?

04:13.240 --> 04:14.240
I don't know.

04:14.920 --> 04:16.875
Like, uh, two million?

04:17.839 --> 04:18.839
Two and a half?

04:19.120 --> 04:20.120
I don't know.

04:21.839 --> 04:22.920
You never thought about it?

04:23.920 --> 04:25.035
What does it matter?

04:26.040 --> 04:27.960
Well, aren't you getting
the house when they die?

04:28.920 --> 04:29.920
