36:39.520 --> 36:41.078
or... I don't know. Who was it?

36:41.160 --> 36:43.879
Who was it? Someone...
someone saying, "Where's Brad?

36:45.080 --> 36:46.308
I remember that guy Brad."

36:47.200 --> 36:49.953
Oh, well, I'm just, uh,
just been doing my thing.

36:50.720 --> 36:52.551
Dude, it's good to hear your voice.

36:53.640 --> 36:55.949
My dog took a shit, though,
so I got to pick it up.

36:56.960 --> 36:57.836
Okay.

36:57.920 --> 37:00.798
Well, I'll, um...
I'll talk to you soon, man.

37:00.880 --> 37:02.400
It's really good to talk to you, also.

37:02.440 --> 37:06.319
And, uh, yeah, if you could,
uh, text me that number.

37:07.040 --> 37:08.376
Yeah, yeah, I'll send it right away.

37:08.400 --> 37:11.073
Come to the islands sometime,
brother. Later.

37:12.480 --> 37:13.708
Yeah. Okay.

37:25.000 --> 37:27.080
For a moment,
I imagined Billy's life in Maui,

37:27.480 --> 37:28.708
with two young girlfriends,

37:29.480 --> 37:30.959
and the great sex he must be having.

37:48.720 --> 37:50.120
Then I thought about Melanie

37:51.160 --> 37:52.752
and what was left of our sex life.

38:17.120 --> 38:18.696
Please leave a message for...

38:18.720 --> 38:19.720
Craig Fisher.

38:19.960 --> 38:21.640
...at the beep.

38:22.320 --> 38:24.390
Uh, hey, Craig. It's, uh, Brad Sloan.

38:24.920 --> 38:25.557
How you doing, man?

38:25.640 --> 38:29.997
Uh, I'm in Boston, and, uh, my son...

38:30.120 --> 38:31.633
Um, if you, uh,

38:32.280 --> 38:34.600
if you could... if you have time,
could you give me a call?

38:35.040 --> 38:36.792
Um, it's kind of on the urgent side.

38:37.320 --> 38:39.117
So, uh... thanks, man.

38:52.760 --> 38:55.638
Not being invited to Nick's wedding
confirmed a creeping fear.

38:57.520 --> 38:59.875
Not only had I not lived up
to my own expectations,

39:01.200 --> 39:02.758
I'd failed in the eyes of others.

39:09.000 --> 39:10.319
I pictured the wedding party.

39:11.560 --> 39:12.560
Everyone there,

39:13.560 --> 39:14.879
basking in each other's glow.

39:16.640 --> 39:18.358
It wasn't friendship that bonded them,

39:18.520 --> 39:20.272
but a perceived level of success.

39:22.480 --> 39:24.311
Whether I was forgotten or excluded...

39:25.200 --> 39:26.200
made no difference.

39:29.480 --> 39:30.515
I was off the list.

39:32.200 --> 39:33.200
A nobody.

39:33.720 --> 39:34.720
A nothing.

39:40.720 --> 39:43.553
The world hated me,
and the feeling was mutual.

40:11.800 --> 40:13.480
Are you okay?
'Cause you seem a little off.

40:14.080 --> 40:15.080
Hm.

40:19.280 --> 40:20.759
No. It's just, um...

40:22.040 --> 40:23.040
stupid.

40:24.040 --> 40:25.040
What?

40:26.400 --> 40:28.960
Uh, some, uh, I don't know,
some old friends...

40:29.360 --> 40:30.918
got together and didn't invite me.
Mm.

40:31.000 --> 40:32.991
And so, you know, 'cause...

40:33.720 --> 40:36.393
I guess 'cause I'm not... um...

40:36.880 --> 40:38.576
you know, whatever.

40:38.600 --> 40:39.919
Just, it's random.

40:41.080 --> 40:42.280
What? You're kind of mumbling.

40:42.480 --> 40:45.120
No, it's... no, it's something
I wouldn't have even wanted to go to

40:45.160 --> 40:46.513
even if I was invited, so...
Oh.

40:47.520 --> 40:48.840
Just, I don't know, kind of lame.

40:53.400 --> 40:54.400
I'm sorry.
Mm.

40:54.920 --> 40:55.920
No.

40:57.160 --> 40:58.229
It's ridiculous.

41:00.240 --> 41:01.434
They sound like dicks.

41:02.560 --> 41:03.595
Hmm. Yeah.

41:13.520 --> 41:14.520
Hello?

41:14.960 --> 41:16.200
Hey. It's Craig Fisher.

41:16.480 --> 41:18.152
Hey! Craig.

41:18.840 --> 41:19.840
What's going on?

41:20.160 --> 41:22.435
Is everything okay? Did someone die?
What?

41:23.000 --> 41:25.116
No. No, nobody died.

41:25.840 --> 41:27.558
Well, you sounded kind of weird on your...

41:27.640 --> 41:29.915
on your message,
and you said it was urgent, so I...

41:30.000 --> 41:32.195
No, no, no, no. I'm sorry.
I didn't mean to...

41:32.280 --> 41:35.078
No. It's just, I'm up here
at Cambridge with, uh, my son,

41:35.160 --> 41:36.320
and we're looking at Harvard,

41:36.840 --> 41:39.593
and he had an interview,
or was supposed to,

41:39.680 --> 41:41.796
at the admissions office, and someone...

41:42.520 --> 41:44.556
messed up over there, so, um...

41:45.520 --> 41:46.191
Uh, you know what?

41:46.280 --> 41:47.960
Uh, hang on a second. I'm in a restaurant.

41:50.520 --> 41:52.636
Hey. Yeah.

41:52.720 --> 41:54.233
So, anyway, I heard that you, uh,

41:54.320 --> 41:55.736
teach a class there.

42:03.480 --> 42:06.472
You know what, actually, I...
I'm flying up there tomorrow.

42:07.000 --> 42:08.240
You guys still gonna be around?

42:08.960 --> 42:11.110
Yeah. We're here, uh...
we're here tomorrow.

42:11.200 --> 42:12.920
We're here till Thursday.
We leave Thursday.

42:13.520 --> 42:14.680
Why don't we get some dinner.

42:15.360 --> 42:16.360
That would be great.

42:17.040 --> 42:19.554
Yeah. Oh, and, um... one last thing.

42:20.040 --> 42:23.828
Troy is a musician.
I mean, like, a true prodigy.

42:24.360 --> 42:25.960
And, uh, there's this music professor...

42:26.040 --> 42:28.200
And I'm not just saying that
'cause he's my kid, but...

42:29.720 --> 42:31.517
Hey, Troy. Troy.

42:31.800 --> 42:33.016
What's the name of the professor?

42:33.040 --> 42:34.712
What?
What's the name of... Hang on.

42:38.840 --> 42:40.720
What's the name
of the music professor you like?

42:41.040 --> 42:42.996
Um, Jerome Backaly.

42:43.880 --> 42:44.880
Jerome Backaly.

42:45.280 --> 42:46.713
- Jerome Backaly.
- Yeah.

42:47.520 --> 42:48.600
Sure, I'll give him a call.

42:49.480 --> 42:50.656
That would be terrific, Craig.

42:50.680 --> 42:52.557
That... man, I owe you.

42:52.920 --> 42:55.480
No problem. So, dinner tomorrow.

42:55.880 --> 42:57.800
Yeah, that'll be great.
I'll pick a place.

42:58.160 --> 42:59.229
Have a great taping.

43:00.080 --> 43:01.399
Thanks, man. Bye.

43:02.320 --> 43:03.320
What's going on?

43:04.240 --> 43:05.240
Dad...

43:07.160 --> 43:08.160
I'm on it, okay?

43:09.600 --> 43:10.600
I'm on it.

43:38.040 --> 43:39.040
Mm-hmm.

43:41.000 --> 43:42.911
- Hey, Craig.
- Hey.

43:43.000 --> 43:45.800
Guess what. I'm in a bookstore,
and I'm looking at your book right now.

43:46.360 --> 43:47.760
Great. So, I've got some good news.

43:48.840 --> 43:51.274
Just got off the phone
with the dean of admissions.

43:52.640 --> 43:53.640
Seriously?

43:53.960 --> 43:54.960
You're in luck.

43:57.600 --> 43:59.280
Guess who you have
a meeting with tomorrow.

44:01.280 --> 44:02.474
Who?
Jerome Backaly.

44:04.640 --> 44:05.436
What?
Yeah.

44:05.520 --> 44:08.320
And then after that, you have an interview
with the dean of admissions.

44:10.120 --> 44:11.120
No way.

44:11.160 --> 44:12.160
Way.

44:14.120 --> 44:15.473
Are you serious?
Totally serious.

44:17.840 --> 44:20.274
Wow! Wha...

44:20.360 --> 44:21.952
Oh, jee...

44:22.800 --> 44:24.233
What?
Yeah, man.

44:24.840 --> 44:26.034
Oh, sh...

44:26.240 --> 44:27.434
Now I'm nervous.

44:28.000 --> 44:29.000
No. Come on.

44:30.120 --> 44:31.120
Oh...

44:31.320 --> 44:33.436
Uh... wait, no, shit.

44:33.520 --> 44:35.400
Uh, tomorrow I'm supposed
to have Tufts, though.

44:35.680 --> 44:36.680
Fuck Tufts.

44:37.360 --> 44:39.112
Yeah. Yeah.

44:39.200 --> 44:40.480
Ah... we'll go in the afternoon.

44:40.960 --> 44:42.678
Dad.
Yeah?

44:43.600 --> 44:44.874
You're the fucking king, man.

44:45.960 --> 44:46.960
Gotcha, pal.

44:50.520 --> 44:51.520
What do you think, Troy?

44:54.560 --> 44:56.357
I'm going to Harvard.

44:57.200 --> 44:58.960
Coming through for Troy
made me giddy.

45:00.040 --> 45:01.040
Try it.

45:03.240 --> 45:05.834
Maybe this was the first
in a long series of victories.

45:09.160 --> 45:10.070
Oh, my God.

45:10.160 --> 45:12.993
I pictured Troy as an adult,
happy and wealthy.

45:13.720 --> 45:14.470
Even famous.

45:14.560 --> 45:15.560
I'm getting all of them.

45:18.360 --> 45:19.360
Here you go.

45:19.400 --> 45:20.880
That's our son.
For you. It's our son.

45:21.800 --> 45:22.800
It's our son.

45:23.680 --> 45:24.908
I love you both so much.

45:25.520 --> 45:27.556
And all my success is because of you.

45:28.240 --> 45:29.673
Aw.
Oh.

45:29.760 --> 45:31.478
Thank you. Thanks, buddy.
And guess what.

45:32.080 --> 45:33.080
What?

45:33.800 --> 45:34.800
I bought an island!

45:35.000 --> 45:35.637
What?

45:35.720 --> 45:37.711
Yeah!

45:37.800 --> 45:40.598
I pictured his triumphs eclipsing
those of my contemporaries.

45:43.360 --> 45:44.918
And how gratifying that would be.

46:00.440 --> 46:01.873
Suddenly, my thoughts darkened.

46:03.120 --> 46:04.235
These victories...

46:05.280 --> 46:07.032
how desperate to claim them as mine.

46:09.440 --> 46:10.440
They would be his.

46:11.600 --> 46:14.319
Um... my dad,
like, whenever he sees

46:14.400 --> 46:16.630
a photo of me on the Internet
or in a magazine,

46:17.440 --> 46:19.476
for some reason he thinks it's,
like, my obituary.

46:19.800 --> 46:22.189
And that I've, like, died.

46:22.280 --> 46:24.475
It sounds like your dad
might be a little bit crazy.

46:24.560 --> 46:27.393
Crazy? Uh, yeah, a little.
I would say, um...

46:27.480 --> 46:29.789
- Like, maybe this?
- Maybe, yeah.

46:29.880 --> 46:31.696
- A little bit more.
- Maybe a little more than that.

46:31.720 --> 46:34.359
- Maybe a little bit more than a little.
- Yeah, yeah.

46:35.040 --> 46:37.031
What if Troy lorded
his success over me,

46:37.800 --> 46:38.949
or hoarded it away?

46:39.480 --> 46:41.656
It sounds like your father
might be mentally ill,

46:41.680 --> 46:42.795
in need of some help.

46:44.320 --> 46:45.435
What if, in the end,

46:46.080 --> 46:48.310
Troy's wins made me feel
even more the failure?

46:53.480 --> 46:55.471
What if I became envious of my own son?

46:59.720 --> 47:01.199
The thought horrified me.

47:02.640 --> 47:04.358
Lose yourself in nature

47:04.440 --> 47:06.112
And find peace

47:08.400 --> 47:10.755
Troubles will come

47:10.840 --> 47:12.796
Troubles will release

47:13.640 --> 47:17.189
Lose yourself
In nature and find peace

47:18.640 --> 47:19.640
Then again...

47:20.360 --> 47:21.952
musicians rarely make money.

47:23.400 --> 47:24.628
Even with a Harvard education,

47:24.720 --> 47:26.631
Troy could easily end up
a struggling artist.

47:33.000 --> 47:35.389
Troubles will come

47:35.480 --> 47:37.516
Troubles will release

47:38.320 --> 47:41.392
Lose yourself in nature and find peace

47:45.240 --> 47:47.879
Chickens and children know it all...

47:48.640 --> 47:50.400
Or maybe he'll
take after Melanie...

47:51.800 --> 47:54.234
perfectly satisfied
with practically nothing.

47:56.120 --> 47:58.190
We may reach great heights

47:58.440 --> 48:00.192
But ever will we fall

48:01.480 --> 48:04.199
Chickens and children know it all

48:07.880 --> 48:11.509
Lose yourself in nature and find peace

48:13.400 --> 48:17.359
Lose yourself in nature
And find peace

48:19.120 --> 48:20.792
Hey, if you're just gonna be a musician,

48:22.240 --> 48:23.600
do you even need to go to college?

48:26.840 --> 48:27.840
What?

48:29.080 --> 48:30.080
It's a fair question.

48:32.400 --> 48:34.391
- "Just" a musician?
- Yeah.

48:34.840 --> 48:36.456
I'm just saying,
do you need a Harvard diploma

48:36.480 --> 48:37.960
if you're gonna play music in a band?

48:38.160 --> 48:39.400
Isn't that what you want to do?

48:42.760 --> 48:44.239
I don't know what I want to do, Dad.

48:44.720 --> 48:47.040
Okay, well, you better start thinking
about it, 'cause, uh,

48:47.240 --> 48:50.038
this isn't cheap, Troy,
and you're assuming a lot

48:50.120 --> 48:53.317
if you think that I can pay for all this
without taking out loans,

48:53.400 --> 48:56.676
or you taking out loans,
or trying to get scholarships

48:56.760 --> 48:58.273
or financial aid.

48:58.720 --> 48:59.840
What the fuck just happened?

49:00.920 --> 49:03.681
I'm thinking out loud, okay?
I don't expect you to pay for everything.

49:08.080 --> 49:10.096
I mean, are you not gonna
be able to pay for everything?

49:10.120 --> 49:12.160
We'll see. I don't want
you to worry about this yet.

49:12.960 --> 49:13.960
Clearly.

49:14.040 --> 49:16.960
Hey, it might not be a big issue.
Maybe one of your grandparents will die.

49:27.800 --> 49:28.869
- Hey.
- Hey.

49:29.960 --> 49:31.791
How you doing?
Good. How are you?

49:33.480 --> 49:34.515
This is my dad, Brad.

49:34.600 --> 49:36.477
Hey, Dad-Brad. I'm Ananya.

49:36.960 --> 49:40.236
Hey. So, you guys were friends
at Country Day?

49:41.120 --> 49:42.439
We were in orchestra together.

49:42.480 --> 49:44.680
- Yeah, Ananya's a really amazing musician.
- Really?

49:44.880 --> 49:46.791
Uh-huh.
And now you go to Harvard.

49:47.160 --> 49:48.718
Yeah. I'm a junior.
That's... Wow.

49:48.800 --> 49:50.870
Are you liking it?
Yeah, it's great.

49:51.080 --> 49:54.550
I mean, it gets really cold,
but I love my classes.

49:54.640 --> 49:55.868
Really great people.

49:55.960 --> 49:58.030
Yeah, no complaints.

49:58.400 --> 50:01.073
Uh, I made a reservation
at a restaurant around the corner.

50:01.160 --> 50:02.115
So, should we go?

50:02.160 --> 50:03.434
Yeah.
Cool.

50:03.600 --> 50:04.600
Let's do it.
Mm.

50:09.720 --> 50:11.438
It's good to see faces from home.

50:12.360 --> 50:14.555
It's so cool you got that
meeting with Jerome Backaly.

50:14.960 --> 50:15.960
How'd you manage that?

50:16.000 --> 50:17.656
Oh, my dad's friends
with a professor here.

50:17.680 --> 50:18.476
Oh, yeah?
Mm-hmm.

50:18.600 --> 50:19.600
Yeah.
Who?

50:20.360 --> 50:21.360
His name's Craig Fisher.

50:23.640 --> 50:24.640
Oh... What?

50:25.520 --> 50:26.520
What?

50:26.560 --> 50:27.560
You made a face.

50:28.200 --> 50:30.509
I did?
Yeah, you definitely made a face.

50:30.600 --> 50:32.240
It's okay, you can say whatever you want.

50:32.360 --> 50:33.480
We're not close or anything.

50:33.720 --> 50:35.000
We were friends a long time ago.

50:35.880 --> 50:37.996
Well, I took his class last year,

50:38.080 --> 50:40.230
and... he's kind of the worst.

50:41.480 --> 50:43.596
Should I not have said that?

50:43.680 --> 50:45.830
No, say it. What?
He's just...

50:46.360 --> 50:48.669
he's condescending, and...

50:49.560 --> 50:50.959
I don't know, he's pretty sexist.

50:51.840 --> 50:53.796
He's got this air of someone who thinks

50:53.880 --> 50:56.713
that they know everything
just because he's on TV

50:56.800 --> 50:58.791
and has got contacts at the White House.

50:59.760 --> 51:00.880
But, how do you really feel?

51:01.520 --> 51:02.856
Honestly, by the end of his class,

51:02.880 --> 51:04.438
I wanted to quit my major, so...
Mm.

51:05.120 --> 51:06.553
Uh, aren't you a music major?

51:07.360 --> 51:08.360
No, government.

51:08.480 --> 51:10.471
My, uh, dad majored in government.

51:10.600 --> 51:12.875
Oh, yeah?
Yeah, communications and government.

51:12.960 --> 51:13.960
This was at Tufts.

51:14.440 --> 51:15.759
So, what do you do now?

51:16.240 --> 51:18.356
I have a nonprofit I started
a few years ago.

51:18.760 --> 51:19.988
- Really?
- Yeah, yeah.

51:20.080 --> 51:22.833
We, uh, help other nonprofits
use social media

51:22.920 --> 51:24.480
to get the word out about what they do.

51:24.920 --> 51:26.273
You know, find donors, members.

51:26.440 --> 51:28.078
So, is it, like, crowdsourcing or...

51:28.240 --> 51:29.832
Um, a little bit of that.

51:29.920 --> 51:31.120
Basically, we're a consultant.

51:31.760 --> 51:33.280
Sounds boring, but...
Cool. No, no, no.

51:33.400 --> 51:34.400
It doesn't sound boring.

51:34.480 --> 51:35.480
It sounds amazing.

51:35.600 --> 51:36.749
Oh. Well, thanks.

51:36.960 --> 51:38.996
Yeah. Um, actually, I'm...

51:39.080 --> 51:41.594
I'm writing my thesis on NGOs.

51:41.920 --> 51:43.520
Maybe I could talk to you at some point?

51:43.880 --> 51:45.871
Of course. Whatever you need.
Cool.

51:46.920 --> 51:47.920
Thank you.

51:48.480 --> 51:49.993
So, tell us about your thesis.

51:50.360 --> 51:51.360
Really?
Yeah.

51:51.600 --> 51:52.715
You want to know?
Yeah.

51:52.960 --> 51:55.918
Okay, well, um, uh,
it's not fully formed yet,

51:56.200 --> 51:59.875
uh, but I want to write about the history
of white missionary women.

52:00.120 --> 52:01.439
Like, you know, the wives

52:01.720 --> 52:03.790
who went to lndia
and Sri Lanka to, you know,

52:03.880 --> 52:06.155
like, "convert the heathens," but, really,

52:06.240 --> 52:08.037
they laid down a lot of groundwork

52:08.120 --> 52:09.712
for social reform...

52:10.200 --> 52:11.200
I remember this.

52:13.800 --> 52:14.800
This feeling.

52:17.360 --> 52:19.874
This girl, with all her idealism,

52:21.560 --> 52:22.629
her sense of purpose,

52:24.480 --> 52:25.480
her hope.

52:26.840 --> 52:28.637
...as it relates
to women's rights,

52:28.720 --> 52:32.190
and how one of the sad legacies
of colonialism

52:32.280 --> 52:34.555
is that they really had no part...

52:34.640 --> 52:35.880
I remember these nights.

52:37.320 --> 52:38.469
These conversations.

52:39.600 --> 52:41.158
The plans to change the world.

52:44.160 --> 52:45.309
A longing to connect.

52:45.800 --> 52:50.191
One time, I told him that my dream job
was to work at Amnesty I nternational,

52:50.320 --> 52:52.595
- and he was, like, devastated.
- Mm.

52:52.840 --> 52:53.896
Mm.
So you're lucky...

52:53.920 --> 52:55.400
you're lucky that your dad's so cool.

52:55.480 --> 52:56.071
- Yeah.
- Oh.

52:56.160 --> 52:57.513
Hey!
Hey!

52:57.840 --> 52:59.480
This is my friend, Maya.
Hey, how are you?

52:59.520 --> 53:00.953
Hey. I told her to stop by.

53:01.080 --> 53:02.416
- I hope that's okay.
- Thank you.

53:02.440 --> 53:04.510
So, uh, you go to Harvard, too?
Yes, I do.

53:05.200 --> 53:06.656
Yeah, uh, Maya's in orchestra with me.

53:06.680 --> 53:08.079
- She plays the violin.
- Oh.

53:08.160 --> 53:09.640
And, uh, what instrument do you play?

53:10.040 --> 53:11.837
I play the flute. Yeah.

53:12.840 --> 53:14.398
- The flute? Oh, wow.
- Yeah.

53:15.360 --> 53:16.936
I just don't feel like it's my job

53:16.960 --> 53:19.315
to be the ambassador
to all these Chinese students.

53:19.840 --> 53:22.040
I mean, of course I want
to help them assimilate, but...

53:22.360 --> 53:25.557
First of all, I'm fucking Korean. Okay?

53:26.080 --> 53:28.116
And second of all,
I don't even speak Mandarin...

53:28.200 --> 53:30.111
Her friend Maya
was equally captivating,

53:30.720 --> 53:31.914
equally compelling.

53:35.480 --> 53:36.879
I suddenly felt a deep grief...

53:39.400 --> 53:40.960
for all the women I would never love...

53:43.520 --> 53:45.192
and all the lives I would never live.

53:55.440 --> 53:57.032
I imagined running away with them both

53:57.120 --> 53:58.680
and starting again.

